Exercise 3.6

First Ill set up some mean, mode, and standard deviation functions to do the calculating for me.

meanbeta <- function(alpha, beta) {
  alpha/(alpha+beta)
}

modebeta <- function(alpha,beta) {
  (alpha - 1)/(alpha + beta - 2)
}

sdbeta <- function(alpha,beta) {
  sqrt((alpha*beta)/(((alpha + beta)^2)*(alpha + beta + 1)))
}

Part A

We can think of the mean visually as the balancing point of the distribution. A, B, D, and F all have means of .5. E has a lower mean than .5, since its more concentrated on the left side. That means it has the lowest mean. C has a higher mean than .5, because its more concentrated on the right side. That means it has the highest mean.

meanbeta(.5,6)
## [1] 0.07692308
meanbeta(6,2)
## [1] 0.75

Es mean is .077, and Cs mean is .75.

Part B

The mode of a beta distribution, visually, is the x-axis location of the highest point on the graph of the f(\(\pi\)) function. E has the lowest mode, because its highest point occurs at/near 0. C has the highest mode, because its highest point occurs the farthest right. (I didnt count A, since it is bimodal, but technically it has the lowest AND highest means (0 and 1).)

## modebeta() won't work for E because alpha and beta are below 1, so I just used common sense to figure this one out.
modebeta(6,2)
## [1] 0.8333333

Es mode is 0, and Cs is .83.

Part C

The one with the smallest standard deviation is basically the one that is spread out the least, which in this set is E. The one with the highest standard deviation is one that is spread out the most, which in this set would be A.

sdbeta(.5,6)
## [1] 0.09730085
sdbeta(.5,.5)
## [1] 0.3535534

Es standard deviation is .097. As is .354.

Exercise 3.11

Part A

Since the mean is .25, we know that (alpha)/(alpha+beta) = .25, which also means that beta is 3 times alpha. Since the mode is 5/22, alpha must be 6 and beta must be 18, because (6-1)/(6+18-2) = 5/22 and $ 6*3 = 18 $. Plotting Beta(6,18)

plot_beta(6,18)

Part B

Using plot_beta_binomial() and summarize_beta_binomial() to specify the posterior

plot_beta_binomial(6, 18, y=15, n=50)

summarize_beta_binomial(6, 18, y=15, n=50)
##       model alpha beta      mean      mode         var         sd
## 1     prior     6   18 0.2500000 0.2272727 0.007500000 0.08660254
## 2 posterior    21   53 0.2837838 0.2777778 0.002710007 0.05205773

The posterior model for \(\pi\) is Beta(21,53).

Part C

summarize_beta_binomial(6, 18, y=15, n=50)
##       model alpha beta      mean      mode         var         sd
## 1     prior     6   18 0.2500000 0.2272727 0.007500000 0.08660254
## 2 posterior    21   53 0.2837838 0.2777778 0.002710007 0.05205773

The mean of the posterior is .284, the mode is .278, and the standard deviation is .052.

Part D

I would say that the posterior more closely resembles the data than the prior, which makes sense because the prior model is equivalent to a survey of approx. 22 people, while the data is a survey of 50 people - you would expect a larger sample to sway our opinion more.

Part C

Patrick and Harolds posterior models look very similar in overall size and shape; theyre both centered around .7-ish, and both look much more similar to the data than the prior. The difference is that Harolds posterior is more broad (less confident) than Patricks; and theres a tiny bit more daylight in between Harolds posterior and data than between Patricks. The reason for this is that even though they had the same exact prior, and their data actually told them the same thing (75% attended a protest), Patricks larger sample size allows him to be more confident about his conclusions and pulls his posterior closer to the likelihood. Thats why Patricks posterior is steeper and a tiny bit farther right than Harolds.
